Tennis season is coming up. I haven’t played gor a few years. But years ago I found an old tennis racquet named “Wilding” named for my forbear world icon Wimbledon and Grand Slam and Olympic medalist winner Anthony Wilding.  I found the racquet in an old antique store in Oklahoma of all places driving across country. Turns out the original Wilson company had used his name in 1933, without permission . He passed away in World War 1 at the age of 32 in 1915. I got a lawyer as upon research it turned out that the company that became Wilson had pretty much founded itself and made all its money on these rackets. Millions in fact- in 1933. Anthony Wilding only won ten pounds his entire career as spirts were not professional back then. NY Times interviewed me and wrote a feature but they could only say so much without Wilson going after them. You see Wilson were not sportsman about the entire matter. They were offered ways to settle with the family- backing my charity all sorts of things- and they were outright nasty. We won’t use Wilson rackets ever again. They are not sportsman and made their money off late veteran’s lives without permission  #tennis

Congrats @carlitosalcarazz  I am bummed I missed Wimbledon this year! Wimbledon - I love it .
My forbear won 10 times- Singles , double , mixed.  To keep fit , he practiced with boxing champs and he was the first man to take a motorbike solo round Europe. He used to sleep on the top of the Monte Carlo Tennis Club roof top before winning the championships there too. 
He lived in London, played Forrest Hills in Queens befire the new Grand Slam stadium, was from NZ, and travelled by boat- to and from NZ - took six weeks each time.

The first ever cigarette cards , invented in France, featured him. I found one on ebay. 

Tragically Captain Anthony Wilding was killed by the German’s in WW1 in his 30’s. 

I followed sime of his route when I went to find his grave in Flanders years ago- accompanied by a great Italian journalist Stefano Semararro - who wrote a fabulous four page article published in Ace, Tennis Magazine and Italian sports mags. The game was amateur in those times. He won 10 pounds only. I have many stories surrounding his life and my journey to find out and piece together more of his. 

Here’s to sports history and the legends of old #tennis #wimbledon2023 #wimbledontennis #historymemes

Step into Tangier in 1928. The way it was. History in the blink of an eye. This artwork is a collaboration between myself and a late family member who was a professional artist as well. This exotic piece was originally painted in 1928 . I have now bought this much loved personal piece from my own collection into the present day of NFT's exploring the use of color, light fragments and animation to represent the blink of a camera. Just as I capture rare pure raw moments in time through the lens , the collectible painters of old captured with their paint brush. I also explore and use paint and other techniques with some of my works. In a way this is a reversal..starting with the raw painting by Cora , working my way through a multitude of digital paint brush strokes and other techniques, and ending up with a camera click . Tangier the way it was through a multiple blend of raw paint, digital paint, camera artistry and use of tool box and multiple skill sets. Enjoy . Cora Wilding studied art in Florence, exhibited and is still collected to this day. Cora Wilding was traveling by herself in Morocco as a young woman way back in 1928. I grew up in a family that embraced all cultures. Enjoy this rare artwork form my home to your home or gallery , capturing a moving moment in time!
